	<h1>Annotations</h1> 
	
	Tapestry doesn't just look for particular method names - it also looks for particular annotations. Here are some useful ones...<br/><br/>
	<strong>@OnEvent(value = EventConstants.ACTIVATE).</strong> You can put this annotation on a method instead of naming the method <em>onActivate</em>.<br/><br/>
	<strong>@SetupRender.</strong> You can put this annotation on a method instead of naming the method <em>setupRender</em>.<br/><br/>
	<strong>@CleanupRender.</strong> You can put this annotation on a method instead of naming the method <em>cleanupRender</em>.<br/><br/>
	<strong>@Log.</strong> If you put this annotation on a method then Tapestry will log calls to the method at debug level.<br/><br/>
	<strong>@Property.</strong> If you put this annotation on a field then Tapestry will invisibly provide a getter and setter 
	for the field.  If the field has a leading underscore, Tapestry will generate the getter and setter names <em>without</em> the
	underscore.<br/><br/>

	The value of field <code>_message</code> is "<span style="color:red">${message}</span>".<br/><br/>

	References: 
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/tapestry5/guide/rendering.html">Component Rendering</a>, 
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/tapestry5/guide/logging.html">Logging</a>.<br/><br/>

